Task 1: Understanding Your Network Interface Configuration
Subtask 1.1: View Network Interfaces Using Modern Commands
Let's start by examining your machine's network configuration using current Linux commands.

Step 1: Open your terminal and run the modern IP command to view all network interfaces:

ip addr show
Step 2: For a cleaner output, you can use the shortened version:

ip a
What You're Seeing: • lo (loopback): Internal interface for local communication • eth0 or enp0s3: Your main network interface • inet: Shows IPv4 addresses • inet6: Shows IPv6 addresses

Subtask 1.2: Using the Traditional ifconfig Command
Step 3: Now let's use the traditional ifconfig command (still widely used):

ifconfig
If ifconfig is not available, install it:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install net-tools -y
ifconfig
Step 4: View only active interfaces:

ifconfig -a
Subtask 1.3: Understanding Your IP Address
Step 5: Let's focus on your main network interface. Run this command to see just your primary IP:

hostname -I
Step 6: Get more detailed information about your default route:

ip route show
Key Information to Note: • Your IP address (usually starts with 192.168, 10.0, or 172.16-31) • Your subnet mask (often /24 or 255.255.255.0) • Your default gateway (where traffic goes to reach the internet)

Task 2: Testing Network Connectivity
Subtask 2.1: Basic Ping Testing
Step 7: Test connectivity to your own machine (loopback test):

ping -c 4 127.0.0.1
The -c 4 flag sends exactly 4 ping packets, then stops.

Step 8: Test connectivity to your default gateway. First, find your gateway:

ip route | grep default
Step 9: Ping your gateway (replace X.X.X.X with your actual gateway IP):

ping -c 4 [your_gateway_ip]
Example:

ping -c 4 192.168.1.1
Subtask 2.2: Testing Internet Connectivity
Step 10: Test connectivity to a reliable public DNS server:

ping -c 4 8.8.8.8
Step 11: Test connectivity to a well-known website:

ping -c 4 google.com
Understanding Ping Output: • Time values: Lower is better (measured in milliseconds) • Packet loss: Should be 0% for good connectivity • TTL (Time To Live): Shows how many hops the packet can make

Subtask 2.3: Advanced Ping Options
Step 12: Send larger ping packets to test network capacity:

ping -c 4 -s 1000 google.com
Step 13: Ping with timestamps to see when each response arrives:

ping -c 4 -D google.com
Task 3: Tracing Network Paths with Traceroute
Subtask 3.1: Installing and Using Traceroute
Step 14: Install traceroute if not already available:

sudo apt install traceroute -y
Step 15: Trace the path to a website:

traceroute google.com
Step 16: Use the more detailed tracepath command:

tracepath google.com
Subtask 3.2: Understanding Traceroute Output
Step 17: Let's trace to a specific server and analyze the results:

traceroute -n 8.8.8.8
The -n flag shows IP addresses instead of trying to resolve hostnames, making it faster.

What Each Line Shows: • Hop number: How many routers the packet passed through • IP addresses: The routers along the path • Response times: Three timing measurements per hop • Asterisks (*): Indicate timeouts or blocked responses

Task 4: Exploring DNS Resolution
Subtask 4.1: Basic DNS Lookup with nslookup
Step 18: Look up the IP address of a website:

nslookup google.com
Step 19: Perform a reverse DNS lookup (IP to domain name):

nslookup 8.8.8.8
Step 20: Query a specific DNS server:

nslookup google.com 1.1.1.1
Subtask 4.2: Advanced DNS Queries with dig
Step 21: Install dig if not available:

sudo apt install dnsutils -y
Step 22: Perform a basic dig query:

dig google.com
Step 23: Get just the IP address (clean output):

dig +short google.com
Step 24: Query different record types:

dig google.com MX
dig google.com NS
dig google.com TXT
Subtask 4.3: Understanding DNS Records
Step 25: Get detailed information about DNS resolution:

dig +trace google.com
This shows the complete DNS resolution path from root servers down.

Step 26: Check your local DNS configuration:

cat /etc/resolv.conf
Task 5: Network Troubleshooting Practice
Subtask 5.1: Creating a Network Diagnostic Script
Step 27: Create a simple network diagnostic script. Open a text editor:

nano network_check.sh
Step 28: Add the following script content:

#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Network Diagnostic Report ==="
echo "Date: $(date)"
echo ""

echo "=== IP Configuration ==="
ip addr show | grep -E "inet |UP"
echo ""

echo "=== Default Gateway ==="
ip route | grep default
echo ""

echo "=== DNS Servers ==="
cat /etc/resolv.conf | grep nameserver
echo ""

echo "=== Connectivity Tests ==="
echo "Testing loopback..."
ping -c 2 127.0.0.1 | tail -2

echo "Testing DNS server..."
ping -c 2 8.8.8.8 | tail -2

echo "Testing internet connectivity..."
ping -c 2 google.com | tail -2

echo ""
echo "=== DNS Resolution Test ==="
nslookup google.com | grep -A 2 "Non-authoritative"
Step 29: Make the script executable and run it:

chmod +x network_check.sh
./network_check.sh
Subtask 5.2: Network Performance Testing
Step 30: Test network performance with different packet sizes:

echo "Testing different packet sizes..."
for size in 64 128 512 1024; do
    echo "Packet size: $size bytes"
    ping -c 3 -s $size google.com | grep "min/avg/max"
done
Step 31: Monitor network interfaces in real-time:

watch -n 2 'ip -s link'
Press Ctrl+C to stop the monitoring.

Task 6: Security-Focused Network Analysis
Subtask 6.1: Port Scanning Basics
Step 32: Install netcat for network testing:

sudo apt install netcat -y
Step 33: Test if common ports are open on your local machine:

nc -zv 127.0.0.1 22
nc -zv 127.0.0.1 80
nc -zv 127.0.0.1 443
Subtask 6.2: Network Service Discovery
Step 34: Check what network services are running:

ss -tuln
Step 35: View network connections:

ss -tuln | grep LISTEN
Understanding the Output: • t: TCP connections • u: UDP connections
• l: Listening ports • n: Show numerical addresses

Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Command Not Found
If you encounter "command not found" errors:

# For ifconfig, netstat, etc.
sudo apt install net-tools

# For dig, nslookup
sudo apt install dnsutils

# For traceroute
sudo apt install traceroute
Issue 2: Permission Denied
Some commands may require sudo privileges:

sudo [command]
Issue 3: Network Unreachable
If ping fails:

Check your IP configuration: ip addr show
Verify your default route: ip route show
Test local connectivity first: ping 127.0.0.1
Issue 4: DNS Resolution Problems
If websites don't resolve:

Check DNS servers: cat /etc/resolv.conf
Test with IP addresses: ping 8.8.8.8
Try different DNS servers: nslookup google.com 1.1.1.1
